It’s Wisconsin Wednesday.

Some fun facts:
>While red foxes are known for their vast amount of color morphs, arctic foxes also have them, albeit significantly less. White arctic foxes are completely white in the winter, and in the summer, their coat sheds and they typically turn either grey or brown. On the other hand, blue arctic foxes are much darker, having grey to black patches of fur. Some are even completely dark grey in the winter. In the summer, blue arctic fox pelts change to a darker grey, which isn’t much of a color difference for some.

I write this stuff because it's always been a guilty pleasure. Before that, I was writing in a vacuum, trying to emulate literary level stuff while being quite aware I wasn't hitting it. I tried NaNoWriMo, got a decent bit into it, and even had the misguided confidence to show it to friends. In retrospect, it was tryhard trash, but I guess that's something a lot of writers need to do before actually becoming readable.

Anyway, shit like NaNoWriMo exists for the simple purpose of serving as a goal and community for hobby writers and it is, in my experience, kind of shit at it. I went to a local meeting once. Only once. Online, it was all just "I hit my word count" or "how do I hit my word count?" There's also a writing subreddit where you see this problem: Shitloads of people who barely touch pen to paper asking dumb questions, amateurs with their heads up their asses answering them, and very few people actually getting shit done.

So I don't know, bro. The thought to stop has crossed my mind, but it's more latent embarrassment than feeling shackled to my audience. I like actually having an audience. It's easy to fool yourself into thinking that you're writing as a free spirit without anyone there to echo a return, but the editing, rereading and stuff? That's writing. That's part of it.
